Text.Value: I'm glad to see you're not one to give up.
Most people don't find it so easy to conquer. It's a good thing for us that we aren't 'most people'.
Slay your doubt, and nothing can stop you. Not a demon, not a dragon, and certainly not an illithid worm.
I can't say I have.
Lae'zel's tenacious battle-cries?
Loud enough to wake the dead, and shrill enough to shatter a golden goblet.
I thought it the most terrible noise in all sixteen planes. But there's one even more fearsome than that.
What is it?
The clatter of the rising undead?
Yes, well - ahem. If you'd ever actually heard one, you'd not heard a whimper, but a wail.

EditorData.NodeContext: Hemming and hawing after a slightly lascivious joke.

Text.Value: No, I was thinking of a far more loathsome sound:
Oh, the lad's quite the tease. But he's a charming sort of cad - well, most of the time.
Doubt is the greatest villain we face. Greater than all the Hells' devils, greater than a murderous god.
Yes. It made a terrible howl.
Not even close. I find them comforting, even. What I'm thinking of is far more malicious:
The shrieks of the goblins at the grove's gates?
'It's hopeless', it says. 'Stop resisting. Give up and give in.'
They screeched most horribly, yes - but I know of one even more ruthless:
Incredible, wasn't it? Loud enough to wake the dead, and shrill enough to shatter a golden goblet.
Question for you: have you ever heard a banshee's scream?
No, but I once made one whimper a bit.
Mm - for the best that you haven't. An agonising wail. Loud enough to wake the dead, and shrill enough to shatter a golden goblet.
They do clack out a dreadful rhythm. But the one I'm thinking of is even more dire:
We should rest these weary bones of ours.
I bet it's Astarion's flirtatious drawl.
The doubt in our minds crying out for attention.

Synopsis: The player talks to Wyll on their second night at camp.
